\begin_layout Standard
A powerful feature of LaTeX is its ability and flexibility in allowing internal
 (and external!) referencing.
 You can reference almost anything that is numbered: sections, subsections,
 etc., as well as equations and figures.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Referencing works in two steps: labeling and referencing.
 We provide two illustrations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Referencing Sections
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let's suppose we want to add a reference here directing the reader to the
 section ``Math Basics''.
 To do so, first put your text cursor at the end of the section title, go
 to the top of the LyX document window, and click the 
\family typewriter
\color blue
Insert label
\family default
\color inherit
 icon (the icon with the picture of a label).
 A 
\family typewriter
\color blue
Label
\family default
\color inherit
 window will appear, with a suggested label name automatically filled in.
 You can type another label name if you prefer.
 After you click OK, a grey box with the label name will appear next to
 the section you have labeled.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To reference this label somewhere in your document, simply click the 
\family typewriter
\color blue
Insert cross-reference
\family default
\color inherit
 icon (the icon with the picture of the open book) at the top of the LyX
 document window.
 A 
\family typewriter
\color blue
Cross-reference
\family default
\color inherit
 window will appear, displaying the list of available labels you can reference,
 along with some formatting options.
 Click the label you want to reference, choose your desired reference format,
 then click OK.
 A grey box with the name of the label being referenced will then appear
 in your LyX document; when you compile your document, LaTeX will convert
 this reference into the appropriate number.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For example, referencing the label we added to the section ``Math Basics''
 produces the result: 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Math-Basics"

\end_inset

.
 This is the section number corresponding to the section ``Math Basics''.
 Clearly, the number by itself is a bit ambiguous (your reader will almost
 surely think, ``What the heck is 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Math-Basics"

\end_inset

?'').
 When calling references, try to write some appropriate context for the
 reference.
 For example, we might write ``Read about the essential math features in
 section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Math-Basics"

\end_inset

.''
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Referencing Equations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Referencing numbered equations works exactly the same way.
 Let's say we want to reference the following equation, which we have written
